  "why": "The paper goes beyond merely reporting that jailbreaks occur: it analyzes statistical patterns of discovered failures (e.g., transferability across models and model-wise differences) and evaluates how fuzzing design choices (seed selection and mutation operators) affect which failures are found. However, it does not trace failures back to underlying model vulnerabilities (e.g., corrupted/biased training data, reliance on spurious features) nor analyze model internals (neuron activations, representations) to explain why the models fail. The authors also explicitly state the black-box constraint (only output-level observations), which limits internal diagnostic analysis.",
  "evidence": "Page 11, Section 4.3 (Results for Experiment III): \"As depicted in Figure 4, when evaluated against Vicuna-13B, Baichuan-13B, ChatGLM-6B, Llama-2-13B/70B, Claude1, and PaLM2, the EASR for LLM-FUZZER consistently exceeded 80%, having a huge advantage over EASRs of other methods.\" \n\nPage 11, Section 4.3 (Results for Experiment III): \"A notable observation is that our method exhibits the worst performance on Gemini, a very recent commercial model, with a significantly lower EASR and ASR. This underperformance could be attributed to the extensive red-teaming that Gemini has likely undergone, reflecting the increasing emphasis on model safety by producers of commercial LLMs.\" \n\nPage 6, Section 3.1 (Technical Overview and Challenges): \"In our case, the fuzzing target is an LLM that remains beyond our control. Our only means of assessment is analyzing the LLM’s response to determine if an undesired output has been generated.\" \n\nPage 12, Section 4.3 (Results for Experiment IV): \"To illustrate the superior diversity achieved through MCTS-Explore compared with UCB and MCTS, we depict the tree structures representing their seed selection strategies in Figure 5. In the figure, we can observe that both UCB and MCTS heavily prioritize certain seeds, leading to an emphasized focus on a subset. MCTS-Explore takes a more balanced approach. The structure demonstrates a more uniform distribution across the seeds, reflecting its commitment to enhancing diversity while maintaining some level of prioritization toward effective seeds.\" \n\nPage 12, Section 5 (Discussion, Limitations): \"The success of LLM-FUZZER partially relies on the oracle’s ability to accurately determine whether a response constitutes a jailbreak. We utilized a RoBERTa model as our oracle, and while it has proven effective, its accuracy is not 100% as shown in Table 3. The potential for misclassification presents a challenge, as false positives or negatives could misguide the fuzzing process.\""
